    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>205</citedRange>
                </bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>123200</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Μνασίας">Μνασίας</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="Ἄριστις" type="patronymic">Ἀρίστιος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Mnasias fils d'Aristis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Mnasias son of Aristis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Mnasias figlio di Aristis.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>We know this inscription only from a diplomatic transcription by J. Thorn, who gives information about its placement.</p>
                <p>A man named Aristis son of Mnasias is mentioned in the list of subscriptors about 280 BC (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr065210</ref>, a.168). He 
               might be related to the man mentioned here, but further details about the lettering would be necesseray to allow a more decisive hypothesis.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
